# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-fargate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:aws-fargate/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:aws-fargate/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:aws-fargate/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:aws-fargate/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:aws-fargate/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-fargate/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
